english:
  title: Sacrifice to the Spirit of Kim Inro
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the sixteenth year of Hongzhi, the ninth month, on the seventh day, I, Park Eun of Goryeong, offer this sacrifice of clear wine and simple fruits to the spirit of my departed friend Inro, and speak thus:

    In my youth, ignorant and foolish, I was dismissed by my elders. Yet among my peers, I often heard the name of Inro whispered with reverence. When I entered the Academy, the reports of him grew ever more wondrous, and secretly my heart longed to make his acquaintance, though fate denied us meeting. Day and night I pondered this, and sorrow settled in my breast.

    Then came the examination of the year Byungsin. He rose brilliantly to first place, his splendor reaching the royal court itself. I too passed and followed in his wake. Seeing his countenance, I knew the depth of his virtue. All the ministers and officials, all who wore the court sash, spoke his praises together, saying: "This man may serve in the most demanding posts or rest in the most leisurely offices—nowhere is he unsuited. What would we choose or reject?" He was appointed to the Secretariat, entrusted with historical records. Whether wielding brush or simply observing, all his work bore structure and coherence. The scholars of the Hanlin Academy bowed aside, content to see him placed in the Hall of Jade, unchallenged by any rival.

    I, unworthy, served as his junior then. My spirit was sharp and bold, my voice loud and demanding. Though others rebuked me, I lacked the clarity to reform myself. Only he was willing to encourage me, to warn me gently. When the assembly doubted, he testified for me. When opinion fractured into many parts, his single word settled all dispute. In my memorials, I dared speak dangerous truths, my sleeves full of remonstrances. Were there no others who shared my convictions? Yet none but he stood so unflinchingly at my side. Though bound and fettered, we held fast to our principles with unyielding spirit. Meeting in the depth of night, clasping hands and speaking from the heart, we vowed: "Our loyalty is clear—Heaven itself shall witness." Yet I fell from favor and was cast out, and he too was demoted and sent away. I dwelt in the provinces while he served in the capital. I sent him a poem by the banks of the Yalu River. When he returned, I rode out with my friend Lee to meet him. Under the moonlit gate we spoke of our distant years of longing, laughing it all away in a single moment.

    That winter in the tenth month, we made another appointment, and I set out with wine in hand—but word came that Taekji had fallen ill, and my spirit sank with disappointment. Alone I drank and composed verses, regretting that I could not show them to him. Later, when Tongji received a new posting and rented a house opposite his, I led Taekji there on a night visit. He came leaning on his cane, and we made merry together. Old friends gathering by chance—that night was our most joyful! We lit the candles and drank through the darkness, unmindful of cups or measures. I fell asleep in drunkenness, my snores loud, while he gently reminded me: "The roosters crow—should we neglect the affairs of state for private pleasure?" That single gathering scattered like clouds, and spring passed without another meeting.

    Misfortune descended upon my household. I was consumed by sorrow, and when summer came in the fourth month, I stood alone. Tending to my wife's funeral rites, I ran about in desperation for a hundred li, seeking a tomb inscription from Nam. His prose was brilliant, and Taekji consented to help me. I borrowed a skilled potter to inscribe the stone, yet he, though gravely ill, rose from his bed and took up brush and pen himself—as if to dissolve the resentment even in the nine springs below. After we completed the rites and I returned, his illness had not abated. Many times he requested leave, but the court would not grant it.

    When he served in the Censorate, order and discipline were restored. His righteous remonstrances before the throne amazed all who heard them. The court said: "Such a man—though afflicted—should never be sent to a provincial post. Let him rest and recover, and keep him still occupied with scholarly pursuits." The public opinion was unanimous and the royal favor extraordinary. Yet to receive such favor seemed perilous, like a rider who has lost his reins.

    I went to visit him in the beginning of the seventh month. His steps were difficult, yet his spirit remained vital. I thought of his vigor in prime years and believed that without medicine he would heal. How could I have known that within a fortnight death would separate us?

    When I heard the dreadful news, I could not believe it true. I rushed to his house and stood before him—there was only grief. Alas, in life he never concerned himself with accumulating wealth. In those humble rooms he lived with his wife and children. When guests arrived, there was nowhere to seat them; they could only stand at the threshold. Yet his heart harbored no discontent, and his manner never changed. The children clung about him in need, his widow stands now bereft and alone. When I think of what comes after, my very organs seem to tear.

    They say Heaven blesses the virtuous—yet it seems not always so. Why, then, is such cruelty reserved peculiarly for men like us? That clear countenance, that warm speech—they rise before me as if I hear them still, as if I see them still. The resentment burns within my breast; his image appears in my dreams. With this single cup I offer libation to his spirit and can only weep aloud.

    Alas, come and partake of this sacrifice.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Hongzhi was the era name of the Zhengde Emperor of Ming Dynasty (1488-1505). The sacrifice takes place in 1503.
  - key: ''
    value: The examination 'Byungsin' refers to 1496, when both Park Eun and Kim Inro passed the civil service examination.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Yalu River' (Yalu/Amnok) marked the border between Korea and China, suggesting Inro served in China.
  - key: ''
    value: The repeated references to 'Taekji' and 'Tongji' are fellow officials and friends who appear throughout their shared history.
  - key: ''
